<$fill $name="body">

!! Why a fixed-position widget instead of `tm-modal`?

`tm-modal` produces a centred dialog with a backdrop, intended for forms / confirmations. A slide deck wants the //entire viewport// and its own keyboard semantics — Esc inside a `tm-modal` is hard-coded to close it, which conflicts with the deep-dive stack. A `position: fixed; inset: 0` div sidesteps the framework and gives the widget full control.

!! Why is the widget rendered from a `$:/tags/PageTemplate` tiddler?

Tagging the host tiddler `$:/tags/PageTemplate` ensures it renders once per page and stays mounted across story-river navigation. The `<$reveal>` wrapper then gates the widget on a state tiddler — the widget exists in the page tree but renders nothing until the state flips to `yes`. That makes "open the deck" a one-line state-tiddler write from anywhere.

!! Slide rendering uses `<$tiddler tiddler=…>`, not `<$let currentTiddler=…>`

`<$tiddler>` actually re-runs the rendering pipeline with the named tiddler as `currentTiddler` //for the purposes of field references like `{{!!caption}}`//. `<$let currentTiddler="…">` rebinds the variable but doesn't re-base field references. Layouts read fields, so `<$tiddler>` is the right wrapper.

!! Link interception caveat

Anchors generated by `<$link>` carry the `data-tiddler-title` attribute, which we use for click interception. Anchors from `<$transclude>`-rendered markdown or plain HTML `<a href="…">` won't have it — we fall back to the `href` attribute (stripping a leading `#` if present). External links (whose href doesn't resolve to a tiddler) are left for the browser to handle.

!! Layout re-render

Each navigation tears down the previous slide widget tree (`removeChildDomNodes` on the layout-transclude subtree) and builds a fresh one. This avoids stale state from heavy embedded widgets (e.g. a mindmap inside a slide). The cost is small for ordinary wikitext slides; if you embed a graph or a long-running plugin, factor in the re-init cost.

!! refresh() short-circuit

When attributes change, the widget falls back to `refreshSelf()`. When tiddlers change but attrs don't, we re-evaluate the slides filter and compare grid signatures — if equal, fall through to `refreshChildren`. This keeps the overlay stable when the user edits an unrelated tiddler outside the deck.

</$fill>
</$transclude>
